the sky footage of Fisher's little power play.

1000
01:14:17,948 --> 01:14:20,143
So, let's do it right now
before they can do that.

1001
01:14:20,250 --> 01:14:22,218
Are you deliberately slow?

1002
01:14:23,053 --> 01:14:24,611
What about them?

1003
01:14:25,989 --> 01:14:27,547
What about them?

1004
01:14:27,658 --> 01:14:31,958
They can cash in the chips.
The casino's just gonna think they're tips.

1005
01:14:39,403 --> 01:14:40,836
- Cashing out.
- Thank you.

1006
01:14:40,938 --> 01:14:43,031
- Thank you.
- Thanks, sweetie.

1007
01:14:43,640 --> 01:14:46,074
- Thanks, hon.
- Thank you, baby.

1008
01:14:50,747 --> 01:14:52,806
I love a parade,
don't you?

1009
01:14:53,984 --> 01:14:57,750
You know, there's a word
I don't throw around all that often,

1010
01:14:58,355 --> 01:14:59,583
"Genius".

1011
01:15:28,085 --> 01:15:31,111
Hey, Kianna. Let me hold
your bag for a second.

1012
01:15:31,822 --> 01:15:33,084
Thanks, baby, here.

1013
01:15:33,190 --> 01:15:34,680
Oh, no problem. Anytime.

1014
01:15:34,791 --> 01:15:37,692
- Watch. Watch, watch. Ready?
- Okay, I'm watching. That's beautiful.

1015
01:15:37,794 --> 01:15:38,783
Watch.

1016
01:15:38,895 --> 01:15:42,626
No, it's great, you just need a little, uh,
to get your knee a little higher.

1017
01:16:04,788 --> 01:16:06,312
- Hi.
- Hey.

1018
01:16:07,691 --> 01:16:10,125
So, the Hard Rock
comped me a suite.

1019
01:16:11,361 --> 01:16:13,329
That's cool, that's great.

1020
01:16:16,400 --> 01:16:18,095
You wanna see it?

1021
01:17:20,464 --> 01:17:23,126
All right, take care, Bobby.
All right?

1022
01:17:43,620 --> 01:17:45,144
God, it's cold.

1023
01:17:45,589 --> 01:17:47,489
Hey, what time is it?

1024
01:17:48,458 --> 01:17:51,621
He's only 45 minutes late.
Show a little patience.

1025
01:17:53,029 --> 01:17:55,088
Oh, look.
Here he comes.

1026
01:17:55,899 --> 01:17:57,890
Guys, I'm sorry I'm late.

1027
01:17:58,001 --> 01:17:59,229
Hey, Ben.

1028
01:17:59,503 --> 01:18:01,300
You know, you could try
returning a call once in a while.

1029
01:18:01,405 --> 01:18:03,566
Good of you to show up, man.
It's not like we're cold or anything.

1030
01:18:03,673 --> 01:18:05,038
Yeah, funny.

1031
01:18:06,343 --> 01:18:09,972
- Hey, did you bring it?
- Yeah, I got it. There it is.

1032
01:18:10,080 --> 01:18:13,015
And you're sure you didn't inlay
the software on more space

1033
01:18:13,116 --> 01:18:14,310
than the parameters suggest?

1034
01:18:14,418 --> 01:18:16,443
No. It's just one-fifth
of the free face.

1035
01:18:16,553 --> 01:18:18,544
Let's fire this mother up.

1036
01:18:18,655 --> 01:18:19,917
Beautiful.

1037
01:18:28,765 --> 01:18:29,993
Okay.

1038
01:18:30,534 --> 01:18:31,626
Okay.

1039
01:18:35,138 --> 01:18:36,730
What's happening?

1040
01:18:40,076 --> 01:18:42,601
- I don't understand.
- It's the wrong size.

1041
01:18:42,712 --> 01:18:43,974
No. What?

1042
01:18:45,048 --> 01:18:48,347
- What the hell, Ben? This is an 8K.
- Right.

1043
01:18:50,020 --> 01:18:51,920
Yeah, we needed 16K!

1044
01:18:53,356 --> 01:18:57,156
I can't believe this.
- I-I thought it was an-an 8K.

1045
01:18:57,260 --> 01:18:58,852
- No, you didn't.
- Yeah, I did.

1046
01:18:58,962 --> 01:19:03,194
No, you didn't. You knew the entire
time the discrete was 16K.

1047
01:19:03,700 --> 01:19:04,962
Damn it, Ben.

1048
01:19:05,068 --> 01:19:08,333
It's gonna take us two weeks
to get a fresh 16K from the fabrication.

1049
01:19:08,438 --> 01:19:11,839
And another five days, minimum,
to get it ready to press.

1050
01:19:11,942 --> 01:19:15,378
Miles, calm down, all right?
It was, uh, an honest mistake.

1051
01:19:18,014 --> 01:19:19,311
What?

1052
01:19:21,651 --> 01:19:26,418
You know what? Um, I think we're gonna
have to go at this without you, man.

1053
01:19:27,524 --> 01:19:29,219
You-you're gonna what?

1054
01:19:32,062 --> 01:19:35,657
No, no. This is just
as much mine as it is yours.

1055
01:19:35,765 --> 01:19:38,359
We've been working on this
for over a year.

1056
01:19:38,468 --> 01:19:42,029
I know that. But your heart
just isn't in this anymore.

1057
01:19:47,811 --> 01:19:49,369
You serious?

1058
01:19:56,086 --> 01:19:57,110
Fine.

1059
01:19:58,955 --> 01:20:00,047
Fine.

1060
01:20:01,458 --> 01:20:05,690
You know what? I don't even care.
Honestly, I don't even care.

1061
01:20:05,795 --> 01:20:07,023
You know why?

1062
01:20:07,130 --> 01:20:11,499
'Cause no one in the real world gives
a shit about the 2.09 Competition.

1063
01:20:12,602 --> 01:20:14,467
You know, it's just something
that you build up in your head

1064
01:20:14,571 --> 01:20:16,562
to make yourselves
feel important.

1065
01:20:16,673 --> 01:20:18,573
You guys are pathetic.

1066
01:20:18,675 --> 01:20:19,835
Thanks.

1067
01:20:26,816 --> 01:20:28,215
Welcome back, Mr. Youngman.

1068
01:20:28,318 --> 01:20:32,084
- Thanks, Joseph. It's good to see you.
- Good to see you, too.

1069
01:20:35,725 --> 01:20:38,717
Good evening, Mr. Youngman,
welcome back to the Red Rock.

1070
01:20:38,828 --> 01:20:40,295
Nice to see you.

1071
01:20:40,397 --> 01:20:43,059
Anything I can do for you,
let me know.

1072
01:21:00,617 --> 01:21:01,982
Double down.

1073
01:21:37,721 --> 01:21:40,747
I guess you play big
or you don't play at all.

1074
01:21:41,958 --> 01:21:43,186
Right?

1075
01:21:45,695 --> 01:21:49,722
Honey, there you are. Let's go.
We don't wanna miss the show!

1076
01:21:49,833 --> 01:21:52,631
Honey, we're actually
playing a game here.

1077
01:21:53,103 --> 01:21:54,195
Yeah.

1078
01:21:54,604 --> 01:21:56,367
Yeah, so,
you know what?

1079
01:21:56,473 --> 01:22:00,534
Why don't you run upstairs
and, uh, wait for me there? Okay?

1080
01:22:03,146 --> 01:22:04,977
All right. Let's go.

1081
01:22:10,153 --> 01:22:12,144
Yeah, all right.

1082
01:22:12,756 --> 01:22:15,350
I've got the worst
headache right now.

1083
01:22:29,372 --> 01:22:31,203
- Ten.
- Come on, monkey.

1084
01:22:31,307 --> 01:22:33,673
- Fourteen.
- Come on. Come on, monkey.

1085
01:22:33,777 --> 01:22:35,904
- Sixteen.
- Monkey. Come on.

1086
01:22:37,213 --> 01:22:38,646
Twenty-one.

1087
01:22:45,088 --> 01:22:47,022
Pete, you're killing us.

1088
01:23:00,270 --> 01:23:02,261
I guess it's not my night.

1089
01:23:27,067 --> 01:23:29,277
Are you out of your mind?

1090
01:23:29,943 --> 01:23:32,725
I, uh, I don't know
what happened.

1091
01:23:33,002 --> 01:23:35,630
I-I messed up.
I'm sorry.

1092
01:23:36,011 --> 01:23:38,034
Oh, oh, you're sorry.

1093
01:23:38,141 --> 01:23:41,736
Oh, see, now that's what I've been waiting
to hear, Ben. As long as you're sorry.

1094
01:23:41,845 --> 01:23:46,407
I'm out 200 grand, but Ben's sorry!
Everybody hear that? Ben's sorry!

1095
01:23:46,516 --> 01:23:50,577
So, we can all go back to being
friends and laughing over cocktails!

1096
01:23:51,788 --> 01:23:53,153
Come on, Micky.
It can happen to anyone.

1097
01:23:53,256 --> 01:23:54,689
They get on a rush
and they lose control.

1098
01:23:54,791 --> 01:23:56,418
You shut your mouth.
This is business.

1099
01:23:56,526 --> 01:23:59,893
Hey, I let you down,
all right? I get it.

1100
01:23:59,996 --> 01:24:03,830
Excuse me? You let me down?
I don't care!

1101
01:24:04,467 --> 01:24:07,595
Let me make one thing clear to you,
I am not your father!

1102
01:24:07,704 --> 01:24:10,730
You are not my friend.
This is a business.

1103
01:24:11,007 --> 01:24:13,134
You are only as good to me
as the money you make,

1104
01:24:13,243 --> 01:24:14,938
and, right now, it's not
worth a hell of a lot!

1105
01:24:15,044 --> 01:24:16,525
You're gonna give me back
everything you lost.

1106
01:24:16,525 --> 01:24:19,644
No, no, no! I can't do that!
That money was for Harvard!

1107
01:24:19,749 --> 01:24:21,649
I have made you so much more
than what I just lost!

1108
01:24:21,751 --> 01:24:23,582
It doesn't matter, Ben.

1109
01:24:23,686 --> 01:24:26,814
You had very clear instructions,
and you didn't follow them.

1110
01:24:26,923 --> 01:24:30,859
You didn't do your job.
You weren't counting, you were gambling!

1111
01:24:33,396 --> 01:24:36,233
Well, why aren't you
out there, then, Micky? Hmm?

1112
01:24:36,866 --> 01:24:41,565
I mean, we take all the risks.
Seems to me like you don't do shit.

1113
01:24:46,276 --> 01:24:48,210
This isn't about me,

1114
01:24:49,045 --> 01:24:52,742
you arrogant little infant.

1115
01:25:05,662 --> 01:25:08,290
You can all find your own way
back to Boston.

1116
01:25:08,398 --> 01:25:12,459
And, Ben, you're gonna pay me that money,
every penny, one way or the other.

1117
01:25:12,569 --> 01:25:14,560
And you damn well
know it.

1118
01:25:24,647 --> 01:25:26,137
I need a drink.

1119
01:25:28,985 --> 01:25:30,418
Anybody else?

1120
01:25:33,456 --> 01:25:35,185
Yeah, well,
we don't need him.

1121
01:25:35,291 --> 01:25:36,952
- Yeah, okay, Ben.
- No, I'm serious.

1122
01:25:37,060 --> 01:25:39,722
Why do we need him?
We have our own money now.

1123
01:25:39,829 --> 01:25:43,094
You know, his cut was 50%,
and he doesn't even play!

1124
01:25:43,666 --> 01:25:44,826
Why do we need him?

1125
01:25:44,934 --> 01:25:46,026
Hey, you know what I think?

1126
01:25:46,135 --> 01:25:49,468
I think we play out the weekend,
and I think we do this without him.

1127
01:25:49,572 --> 01:25:50,971
No. No, I don't think
that's a good idea.

1128
01:25:51,074 --> 01:25:53,304
I think we should go back
to Boston and figure this out.

1129
01:25:53,409 --> 01:25:55,206
Yeah, well, why don't we
let the team decide?

1130
01:25:55,311 --> 01:25:58,439
I'm with Jill. This is Micky's thing.
Micky brought us together.

1131
01:25:58,548 --> 01:26:00,539
And then he drove us apart.

1132
01:26:00,650 --> 01:26:03,676
I mean, you saw how
he played Fisher against me.

1133
01:26:04,621 --> 01:26:08,250
Choi, what do you say, man?
You wanna make some money?

1134
01:26:09,759 --> 01:26:11,420
- Kind of.
- Really?

1135
01:26:12,195 --> 01:26:15,460
We need 100 grand just to play.
You're talking about risking our own money.

1136
01:26:15,565 --> 01:26:17,062
All I'm saying is
that we try it.

1137
01:26:18,014 --> 01:26:22,635
You know, if... we make the investment,
then we take all of the winnings.

1138
01:26:23,706 --> 01:26:25,003
All of it.

1139
01:26:32,148 --> 01:26:33,445
Okay.

1140
01:26:37,754 --> 01:26:38,812
Yeah.

1141
01:26:39,289 --> 01:26:41,348
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

1142
01:26:43,092 --> 01:26:44,286
Choi?

1143
01:26:45,662 --> 01:26:46,924
I'm in.

1144
01:26:48,798 --> 01:26:50,493
Now I need a drink.

1145
01:26:56,472 --> 01:26:58,235
- What are you doing?
- What?

1146
01:26:58,341 --> 01:27:00,309
What are you doing?

1147
01:27:00,410 --> 01:27:02,469
Well, we're printing money.

1148
01:27:02,912 --> 01:27:05,608
What, you think just 'cause Micky
left we're gonna stop?

1149
01:27:05,715 --> 01:27:08,513
No, I could do this.
I can lead this team.

1150
01:27:08,885 --> 01:27:12,150
You know, I'm not the same guy
I was back in Boston.

1151
01:27:12,622 --> 01:27:14,852
- Exactly.
- Yeah, exactly.

1152
01:27:15,358 --> 01:27:17,986
You know, isn't this exactly
who you wanted me to be

1153
01:27:18,094 --> 01:27:21,086
when you first came into
the store to buy a tie?

1154
01:27:25,368 --> 01:27:28,607
What happened to
"300,000 dollars and I'm out"? Hmm?

1155
01:27:28,972 --> 01:27:31,668
What happened to
"A means to an end"?

1156
01:27:32,608 --> 01:27:35,441
How much do you have?
- What?

1157
01:27:35,545 --> 01:27:37,740
- How much do you have?
- I got enough.

1158
01:27:37,847 --> 01:27:40,077
Come on, Ben. How much do you
have saved back in Boston?

1159
01:27:40,183 --> 01:27:42,708
I've got 315 grand,
all right?

1160
01:27:43,086 --> 01:27:45,384
Then why are you still here?

1161
01:27:46,723 --> 01:27:50,682
Because I wanna still be here.
I like being here.

1162
01:27:51,127 --> 01:27:52,992
So does everybody else.

1163
01:27:53,396 --> 01:27:56,092
So, come on, Jill.
Are you in?

1164
01:28:01,971 --> 01:28:04,735
You are the big player, Ben.

1165
01:28:04,841 --> 01:28:06,206
Yes, I am.

1166
01:28:08,644 --> 01:28:10,544
Yeah, can I get a drink?

1167
01:28:38,474 --> 01:28:40,408
Rose, I wanna thank you.

1168
01:28:41,444 --> 01:28:43,810
You have been
most accommodating.

1169
01:28:44,380 --> 01:28:46,348
All right, that's for you.

1170
01:28:46,649 --> 01:28:48,947
Okay, take care.
Hey, good luck.

1171
01:28:56,526 --> 01:28:58,517
Hey, how we doing here, people?

1172
01:29:09,839 --> 01:29:13,240
Yeah, I'm gonna put you on hold
while I track him down.

1173
01:29:16,846 --> 01:29:18,973
Just got an interesting call.

1174
01:29:21,084 --> 01:29:25,145
There's nobody left to fire us.
Planet Hollywood is our last client.

1175
01:29:27,590 --> 01:29:29,490
I don't know about that.

1176
01:29:35,131 --> 01:29:36,564
This is Cole.

1177
01:29:46,112 --> 01:29:50,141
Ahh, queen of diamonds.
Your lady luck tonight.

1178
01:29:50,646 --> 01:29:52,273
You're doing good.

1179
01:29:52,582 --> 01:29:54,345
You're a real winner.

1180
01:29:59,122 --> 01:30:01,818
Sometimes.
Just like everybody else.

1181
01:30:02,892 --> 01:30:05,087
Now, why don't I believe that?

1182
01:30:07,196 --> 01:30:09,255
Maybe you're just smarter
than everybody else, huh?

1183
01:30:09,365 --> 01:30:12,027
Yeah, I bet it's been
that way your entire life.

1184
01:30:12,135 --> 01:30:15,901
Except it just recently started
paying dividends, am I right?

1185
01:30:17,640 --> 01:30:19,005
I'd split them.

1186
01:30:19,108 --> 01:30:23,545
Deck's heavy as hell and since
I've been here, the true count's at plus 7.

1187
01:30:30,353 --> 01:30:32,446
Kianna. I think we have
a serious problem over there.

1188
01:30:32,555 --> 01:30:34,022
- Walk now!
- Oh, shit. Oh, shit!

1189
01:30:34,123 --> 01:30:37,183
Let's go. I'm out. Thank you.
Let's go, Jill. Let's go.

1190
01:30:37,293 --> 01:30:39,022
I think we need to call
security or something.

1191
01:30:39,128 --> 01:30:42,723
Yeah, I don't think they're gonna help.
Let's go! Come on.

1192
01:30:47,336 --> 01:30:49,304
Let's take a walk, huh?

1193
01:30:50,039 --> 01:30:53,805
Come on, kid. See if we can't
get you that chicken dinner.

1194
01:30:58,981 --> 01:31:01,575
It's called, uh,
biometrics.

1195
01:31:01,684 --> 01:31:05,916
Biometrics. It's sort of like,
uh, a fingerprint of your face.

1196
01:31:08,558 --> 01:31:13,791
See, when the player sits down at
the table, the software, it reads this, uh...

1197
01:31:13,896 --> 01:31:15,363
Biometric profile.

1198
01:31:15,464 --> 01:31:17,227
... biometric profile
of your face,

1199
01:31:17,333 --> 01:31:20,359
cross-references it
with a database of counters.

1200
01:31:23,906 --> 01:31:28,707
Software'll probably put you and me
out of business, but it still can't do this.

1201
01:31:31,881 --> 01:31:33,178
All right.

1202
01:31:37,323 --> 01:31:41,621
Ohh! You understand
all this. You go to MIT.

1203
01:31:41,991 --> 01:31:43,390
Smart boy.

1204
01:31:44,860 --> 01:31:46,794
My name is Cole Williams.

1205
01:31:47,396 --> 01:31:50,661
And if I ever see you
in this town again,

1206
01:31:51,434 --> 01:31:54,835
I will break your cheek bone
with a small hammer,

1207
01:31:56,072 --> 01:31:58,063
and then I will kill you.

1208
01:32:02,745 --> 01:32:06,306
Please. Please,
just take the money.

1209
01:32:07,550 --> 01:32:09,074
You can take it.

1210
01:32:11,787 --> 01:32:13,118
Tell me, uh,

1211
01:32:13,689 --> 01:32:18,422
how's... good old
Professor Rosa doing, huh?

1212
01:32:20,096 --> 01:32:24,692
Oh, yeah. Me and Micky,
we go way back.

1213
01:32:25,801 --> 01:32:28,793
I spent years, chased him
all over this town.

1214
01:32:29,238 --> 01:32:34,198
Giving him beat downs left and right,
only to find him at the tables a week later.

1215
01:32:34,310 --> 01:32:36,278
He was very persistent.

1216
01:32:37,179 --> 01:32:40,478
And then, one September night,

1217
01:32:40,983 --> 01:32:43,884
when I was in Barstow
at my father's funeral,

1218
01:32:44,754 --> 01:32:48,190
my casino was taken
for seven figures.

1219
01:32:48,291 --> 01:32:49,622
Can you imagine that?

1220
01:32:49,725 --> 01:32:52,956
The most ever taken by
a single counter in one night.

1221
01:32:53,062 --> 01:32:57,658
'Course I was, naturally,
unceremoniously fired.

1222
01:33:00,369 --> 01:33:02,132
Funny thing, though.

1223
01:33:02,538 --> 01:33:05,063
I never saw Micky Rosa
after that.

1224
01:33:06,242 --> 01:33:07,368
Never.

1225
01:34:34,096 --> 01:34:36,223
Cauchy was the first
to make a rigorous study

1226
01:34:36,332 --> 01:34:40,359
of the conditions for convergence
of an infinite series.

1227
01:34:40,469 --> 01:34:42,767
And was concerned with developing

1228
01:34:42,872 --> 01:34:47,741
the basic theorems of the calculus
as rigorously as possible.

1229
01:34:49,145 --> 01:34:50,578
Any questions?

1230
01:34:50,980 --> 01:34:53,107
No? All right, moving on.

1231
01:34:54,150 --> 01:34:58,143
Isn't it true Cauchy
stole from his students?

1232
01:35:03,058 --> 01:35:06,926
Yes, I heard that.
What's your theory on that?

1233
01:35:07,963 --> 01:35:12,491
They say he used his students
for their brilliance,

1234
01:35:13,636 --> 01:35:17,868
then discredited them
and stole their equations,

1235
01:35:19,942 --> 01:35:21,807
stole their hard work.

1236
01:35:24,513 --> 01:35:27,209
Well, that wouldn't be the first time
a teacher was accused of that.

1237
01:35:27,316 --> 01:35:32,015
I think what he's referring to
is Vladimir Stupnitsky, yes?

1238
01:35:32,121 --> 01:35:35,056
He was a student of Cauchy's
who accused Cauchy

1239
01:35:35,157 --> 01:35:38,490
of stealing his four-volume text
on this analysis

1240
01:35:38,594 --> 01:35:41,062
and publishing it
under a pseudonym.

1241
01:35:42,898 --> 01:35:44,559
Of course, nobody knows
what really went down there.

1242
01:35:44,667 --> 01:35:48,660
They never did prove it, and without
the proof, it's a little like it never happened.

1243
01:35:48,771 --> 01:35:50,796
And, you know,
it's a real shame,

1244
01:35:50,906 --> 01:35:55,104
because if Stupnitsky had just realized
that he shouldn't have crossed Cauchy,

1245
01:35:55,211 --> 01:35:56,940
this was the dispute,

1246
01:35:57,980 --> 01:36:03,976
if he'd been able to... get beyond some
of the personal mistakes that were made,

1247
01:36:04,520 --> 01:36:07,751
I have no doubt that Cauchy
would have worked with him again,

1248
01:36:07,857 --> 01:36:10,883
and they could have
done great things together.

1249
01:36:11,293 --> 01:36:15,354
But, as history shows us,
some students never learn.

1250
01:36:17,066 --> 01:36:18,727
You should get
that eye looked at.

1251
01:36:55,938 --> 01:36:57,337
You okay?

1252
01:37:00,309 --> 01:37:01,936
Everything's gone.

1253
01:37:03,746 --> 01:37:06,340
- What?
- Micky's taken everything.

1254
01:37:06,448 --> 01:37:10,680
He's taken the money,
taken away Harvard Med, even MIT.

1255
01:37:12,555 --> 01:37:14,648
- What are you talking about?
- Micky, he's taken everything.

1256
01:37:14,757 --> 01:37:17,157
I-I-I gotta find a way
to get it back.

1257
01:37:18,460 --> 01:37:19,950
Are you insane?

1258
01:37:20,563 --> 01:37:24,124
You just got the shit kicked out
of you and you won't let this go!

1259
01:37:24,233 --> 01:37:28,169
Look, what am I supposed to do, Jill?
I've just lost everything!

1260
01:37:28,938 --> 01:37:30,428
Look, please...

1261
01:37:32,241 --> 01:37:34,505
I don't wanna lose you, too.

1262
01:37:37,513 --> 01:37:41,108
Ben, you were
dragged away in Vegas.

1263
01:37:41,784 --> 01:37:46,118
I haven't heard from you.
I had no idea where you were.

1264
01:37:46,822 --> 01:37:48,050
I know.

1265
01:37:49,024 --> 01:37:50,184
I know.

1266
01:37:57,533 --> 01:38:00,331
You know, I'm so sorry
that I hurt you.

1267
01:38:02,137 --> 01:38:03,502
I'm sorry.

1268
01:38:06,375 --> 01:38:10,869
In Vegas, I don't know
what happened. That wasn't me.

1269
01:38:12,081 --> 01:38:13,708
Look, you know me.

1270
01:38:14,416 --> 01:38:16,281
You know what I'm like.

1271
01:38:18,087 --> 01:38:19,577
You know me.

1272
01:38:26,028 --> 01:38:27,893
I need you to trust me.

1273
01:38:29,231 --> 01:38:32,598
<i>And the winner of this year's 2.09</i>

1274
01:38:32,701 --> 01:38:38,970
<i>for excellence in the field of robotics
goes to the team of Connolly and Kazazi!</i>

1275
01:39:16,345 --> 01:39:19,314
That's it. That's...
that's the story.

1276
01:39:21,817 --> 01:39:24,047
Jill Taylor. Really?

1277
01:39:24,853 --> 01:39:28,345
- Yeah. Yeah, really.
- Wow.

1278
01:39:28,457 --> 01:39:32,655
Yeah, it doesn't feel like "wow," Miles.
I really screwed up.

1279
01:39:32,761 --> 01:39:37,494
Yeah, you did.
But... you had a life experience.

1280
01:39:41,937 --> 01:39:43,928
I-I can't believe
how I treated you, Miles.

1281
01:39:44,039 --> 01:39:47,941
You know, you're my best friend,
and I... really let you down.

1282
01:39:48,811 --> 01:39:51,905
I really let you down.
I'm sorry.

1283
01:39:53,716 --> 01:39:58,244
And I'm-I'm happy for you, you know?
Winning the 2.09? That's... that's great.

1284
01:39:59,621 --> 01:40:02,089
- Jill Taylor, really?!
- Yeah.

1285
01:40:04,626 --> 01:40:06,719
So, let me get
this straight.

1286
01:40:07,396 --> 01:40:10,559
Money, girls,

1287
01:40:11,734 --> 01:40:16,137
high-roller suites,
clubs, Vegas.

1288
01:40:17,339 --> 01:40:22,367
Yeah, I think I probably would have
blown off the 2.09 Competition, too.

1289
01:40:25,914 --> 01:40:27,279
So, we cool?

1290
01:40:28,917 --> 01:40:30,509
Yeah, we're cool.

1291
01:40:31,019 --> 01:40:33,715
But you better believe that you're
gonna make this up to me big time.

1292
01:40:33,822 --> 01:40:35,084
All right.

1293
01:40:36,391 --> 01:40:38,518
So, what are you
gonna do now?

1294
01:41:29,311 --> 01:41:31,142
What do you want, Ben?
This is an alumni dinner.

1295
01:41:31,246 --> 01:41:33,612
You need a diploma
to come to one of these.

1296
01:41:33,715 --> 01:41:36,115
Wait. Stupnitsky wants back in.

1297
01:41:42,324 --> 01:41:43,291
What?

1298
01:41:43,392 --> 01:41:47,522
Look, I... I've... I've had some time
to think about what you said.

1299
01:41:49,398 --> 01:41:50,888
I want back in.

1300
01:41:51,867 --> 01:41:55,735
- Why now?
- Because I have nothing else.

1301
01:41:57,606 --> 01:42:00,803
All right, look, Ben. I'm not gonna lie to you.
You're good, you're very, very good.

1302
01:42:00,909 --> 01:42:05,073
But you did exactly what I told you not to.
You got emotional and then you got stupid.

1303
01:42:05,180 --> 01:42:08,877
Now you tell me why in the world
I'd ever get back in business with you.

1304
01:42:08,984 --> 01:42:13,444
Look, I know I should never have
disrespected you, all right? I know that.

1305
01:42:14,423 --> 01:42:16,391
With this facial
recognition software,

1306
01:42:16,491 --> 01:42:19,688
our window of opportunity
is closing in on us.

1307
01:42:20,229 --> 01:42:23,892
Now, I need this, Micky.
I really, really need this.

1308
01:42:23,999 --> 01:42:29,130
Well, the take would have to be really, really
good to get me even vaguely interested.

1309
01:42:30,639 --> 01:42:35,941
Well, you know, that's... that's why I was
thinking maybe you should be the other big player.

1310
01:42:37,346 --> 01:42:40,679
You know,
two big players playing big?

1311
01:42:41,850 --> 01:42:45,183
Hey, slow down,
I haven't played in a long time, Ben.

1312
01:42:49,625 --> 01:42:51,217
But Fisher's out.

1313
01:42:52,094 --> 01:42:56,463
No one else on the team
can... be the big player, can they?

1314
01:42:59,701 --> 01:43:03,102
And if we do well,
if we do really well,

1315
01:43:03,872 --> 01:43:07,035
then you get your grades back,
get to Harvard Med,

1316
01:43:08,043 --> 01:43:10,568
and I might even
get that sabbatical.

1317
01:43:11,580 --> 01:43:16,040
Well, amazing things can be done
from the inside, right?

1318
01:43:17,986 --> 01:43:20,682
Just went back to
the head of the class.

1319
01:43:21,957 --> 01:43:23,822
I gotta go be social.

1320
01:43:29,197 --> 01:43:32,496
All right, now listen.
It's different out there this time.

1321
01:43:32,601 --> 01:43:35,468
The stakes are high
and it's more dangerous.

1322
01:43:36,004 --> 01:43:39,064
But the return...
is gonna be the biggest.

1323
01:43:40,375 --> 01:43:43,811
Now, they know our faces,
so we're gonna wear disguises.

1324
01:43:44,046 --> 01:43:46,014
And we can't mess around.

1325
01:43:46,381 --> 01:43:47,848
I'm glad you're
back with us, Micky.

1326
01:43:47,950 --> 01:43:49,850
Well, I couldn't let you guys
come back to this town

1327
01:43:49,952 --> 01:43:53,444
and not prove to Ben that
I can do more than just teach.

1328
01:43:54,289 --> 01:43:58,191
But as we've all said, this game
is about the past and the future,

1329
01:43:58,293 --> 01:44:01,353
and tonight
we forget about the past.

1330
01:44:01,596 --> 01:44:03,461
We just focus on the future.

1331
01:44:03,565 --> 01:44:06,898
Right. This is our last time.

1332
01:44:07,302 --> 01:44:10,328
Now, we all know the drill if things get ugly.
We meet at the Fox Strip Club.

1333
01:44:10,439 --> 01:44:12,771
Nobody leaves this town alone.

1334
01:44:16,244 --> 01:44:18,144
Let's go make a killing.

1335
01:44:18,680 --> 01:44:20,045
All right.

1336
01:44:42,170 --> 01:44:44,638
Let's see what we can do with this.

1337
01:44:53,749 --> 01:44:57,810
Seems like I'm having one of those days,
you know what I mean, Jim?

1338
01:44:59,488 --> 01:45:01,615
I'm bringing all the luck today.
I'm just bringing it all.

1339
01:45:01,723 --> 01:45:06,183
Anyone who's in any kind of contact
with me is getting so much luck today.

1340
01:45:17,839 --> 01:45:20,000
Winner, winner,
chicken dinner! There it is.

1341
01:45:20,108 --> 01:45:23,544
Thank you. God, I love this town.
I love this game.

1342
01:45:24,346 --> 01:45:27,645
And, Jim, I might
even love you.

1343
01:45:37,459 --> 01:45:39,654
Hey, you mind if I sit down?

1344
01:45:53,675 --> 01:45:54,733
What's your name?

1345
01:45:54,843 --> 01:45:57,971
Shane? I'm about to change your luck.
It's gonna become mine.

1346
01:45:58,080 --> 01:46:00,310
There you go,
give me it all.

1347
01:46:10,358 --> 01:46:11,552
There you go.

1348
01:46:14,329 --> 01:46:16,092
Thank you. Thank you.

1349
01:46:20,836 --> 01:46:23,066
Such a shame, Shane!

1350
01:46:24,039 --> 01:46:26,098
Okay, I'm supposed to double, right?

1351
01:46:26,208 --> 01:46:30,542
- Is this your first time, darling?
- I've been winning and losing for hours.

1352
01:46:30,645 --> 01:46:32,738
Well, that's all right.
I've been winning and losing for years.

1353
01:46:46,061 --> 01:46:47,585
What the hell kind of streak
are you on, boy?

1354
01:46:47,696 --> 01:46:50,358
This never happens,
this never happens.

1355
01:47:03,411 --> 01:47:05,208
I'm just gonna have to split those tens.

1356
01:47:05,313 --> 01:47:06,871
- Splitting tens.
- Splitting tens!

1357
01:47:06,982 --> 01:47:08,116
- Split tens!
- Again!

1358
01:47:08,116 --> 01:47:08,844
- Split tens!
- Again!

1359
01:47:31,773 --> 01:47:34,742
- Thank you, ma'am.
- Give me the chips, Blanca.

1360
01:47:35,977 --> 01:47:37,842
Give me the chips!
Come on, give me the chips, Blanca.

1361
01:47:37,946 --> 01:47:40,847
Come on,
just give me the chips!

1362
01:47:40,949 --> 01:47:45,079
- My bus has to leave right away.
- I gotta walk my dog.

1363
01:47:45,187 --> 01:47:47,747
- I'm sorry we're making such a mess.
- Go, go, go, go, go.

1364
01:47:47,856 --> 01:47:50,916
Nice to see you.
Have a good night, darling.

1365
01:47:56,464 --> 01:47:57,761
This way!

1366
01:48:08,977 --> 01:48:10,069
Go.

1367
01:48:24,426 --> 01:48:25,791
This way!

1368
01:48:31,700 --> 01:48:33,691
Come on, Jill.
Come on!

1369
01:48:43,612 --> 01:48:46,206
Go that way. Throw me the chips.
Come on, we gotta separate.

1370
01:48:46,314 --> 01:48:49,181
Give me the chips,
I'll meet you at Fox's.

1371
01:48:55,257 --> 01:48:56,849
Go, go, go, go!

1372
01:49:07,802 --> 01:49:09,463
Come on, come on.

1373
01:49:12,574 --> 01:49:14,132
Move, move, move!

1374
01:49:18,313 --> 01:49:19,575
Come on.

1375
01:49:20,715 --> 01:49:22,307
Go, go, this way.

1376
01:49:34,296 --> 01:49:36,127
All right, let's go.

1377
01:49:44,205 --> 01:49:46,696
Go, go, go, go!
Airport!

1378
01:50:05,260 --> 01:50:06,887
<i>I never saw Micky Rosa
after that.</i>

1379
01:50:11,966 --> 01:50:13,228
Oh, God.

1380
01:50:14,336 --> 01:50:16,600
But I think
I wanna see him now.

1381
01:50:17,672 --> 01:50:20,140
And I want you
to make that happen.

1382
01:50:24,412 --> 01:50:26,846
I-I don't work
for Micky anymore.

1383
01:50:29,851 --> 01:50:31,284
Come on, kid.

1384
01:50:33,121 --> 01:50:36,887
Your picture's all over the database.
Your Vegas gig is done.

1385
01:50:37,926 --> 01:50:39,860
But I will give you
one night.

1386
01:50:39,961 --> 01:50:43,021
And I can guarantee
that you won't be bothered.

1387
01:50:43,932 --> 01:50:47,698
You'll make a killing,
and you'll keep it all.

1388
01:50:50,772 --> 01:50:51,966
Listen.

1389
01:50:53,541 --> 01:50:55,008
My name's Cole.

1390
01:50:56,578 --> 01:50:58,102
Cole Williams.

1391
01:51:00,014 --> 01:51:02,414
You just bring me
Micky Rosa, kid.

1392
01:51:02,717 --> 01:51:04,742
I'll take care of the rest.

1393
01:51:07,288 --> 01:51:10,223
Son of a bitch.

1394
01:51:52,867 --> 01:51:54,630
Who the hell are you?

1395
01:52:17,492 --> 01:52:20,655
Ben. Good job.

1396
01:52:21,729 --> 01:52:26,792
You'll be glad to know I'm gonna have a talk
with your professor, and that MIT thing?

1397
01:52:27,001 --> 01:52:29,094
It's gonna
work out for you.

1398
01:52:30,672 --> 01:52:32,230
So, that's it?

1399
01:52:33,675 --> 01:52:36,439
- That's it.
- All right.

1400
01:52:37,412 --> 01:52:39,107
Oh, dr. Campbell?

